---
description: Tailwind CSS v4 guidelines, including class patterns and shadcn/UI usage.
alwaysApply: false
---
- **Utility-first styling:** Use Tailwind CSS classes for all styling in components. Avoid writing standalone CSS files or styled-components for new styles (unless absolutely necessary for something Tailwind cannot cover). Tailwind’s utility classes should cover most use cases (layout, spacing, colors, typography, etc.). This ensures consistency and theming from the configured design system.
- **Class naming and order:** Organize Tailwind classes in a consistent order when writing JSX. A recommended pattern is: **layout** (display/positioning) -> **box model** (margin/padding) -> **size** (width/height) -> **typography** (font, text-*, etc.) -> **color** (text-color, bg-color, border-color) -> **effects** (shadow, opacity, transitions). For example: `className="flex items-center justify-between p-4 w-full text-sm font-medium text-gray-700 bg-white rounded shadow"` (layout: flex, alignment; box: p-4; size: w-full; typography: text-sm font-medium; color: text-gray-700 bg-white; other: rounded shadow). Consistent ordering makes long class lists easier to read.
- **Reuse through variants:** If you find the same set of Tailwind classes used repeatedly (for example, multiple buttons using `px-4 py-2 font-semibold rounded`), factor this out. Utilize **class-variance-authority (CVA)** to create reusable style variants for components. For instance, define a `buttonVariants` using CVA in the component or a separate styles file, which maps variant names (size = sm/lg, style = primary/secondary) to Tailwind class combinations. This way, applying a variant is just passing a prop (e.g. `<Button variant="primary" size="lg" />`) and the classes are centrally managed. It improves maintainability and consistency for styled components.
- **tailwind-merge for class composition:** When combining multiple class sources, use **tailwind-merge** to merge them safely. For example, if a component allows an incoming `className` prop to override or extend its default classes, do something like: `import { twMerge } from 'tailwind-merge'; ... <div className={twMerge(baseClasses, className)} />`. This will intelligently handle conflicting classes (keeping the last occurrence) and avoid duplications. This is particularly useful when you have conditional classes or are merging classes from CVA with user-provided classes.
- **shadcn/UI patterns:** The components imported from **shadcn/ui** (Radix UI based) come pre-styled with Tailwind. Follow the patterns used in those components when creating new ones. For example, many shadcn components use utility classes and may expose a `className` or `variant` prop to customize styling. When building custom components, consider a similar approach: provide a `className` prop to extend styles and use CVA for variants. Keep all UI components under `src/components/ui` if they are meant to be generic/reusable across the app (mirroring the shadcn structure).
- **Plugin usage (tailwindcss-animate):** For animations, prefer using the classes provided by **tailwindcss-animate** plugin. These classes (like `.animate-spin`, `.animate-fade-in`, etc.) implement common animations and integrate with Tailwind’s duration/easing utilities. This saves time versus writing custom `@keyframes`. Only if a very custom animation is needed should you write custom CSS for it; even then, consider adding it via the Tailwind config as a plugin or extending the theme.
- **Responsive design:** Utilize Tailwind’s responsive modifiers (`sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`, `xl:`) to ensure components are mobile-friendly. Start with mobile-first styles and add larger screen adjustments with breakpoints. Ensure that important layouts work on small screens (test with `sm` or no prefix classes) and scale up. Tailwind’s design tokens (spacing, font sizes, etc.) are generally responsive-friendly, so stick to those to maintain a cohesive look.
- **Avoid inline styles and !important:** Do not use inline `style=` attributes for things that Tailwind can do (which is almost everything, including CSS Grid and Flexbox). Inline styles are harder to maintain and won’t benefit from design tokens or theming. Also avoid `!important` – if you find yourself needing it, rethink the approach (maybe adjust specificity or the order of classes, or use a different approach with Tailwind utilities). The only time inline styles might be needed is for dynamic CSS variables or truly dynamic calculations, but even then consider if those can be handled with Tailwind classes or design tokens.
